During short final Assault Zone landing (RWY18) at Will Rogers WAP, the pilot saw a single bird and crew heard impact.  Due to close proximity ot ground and critical phase of flight, no evasive action was taken.  Flight crew estimated impact on nose of aircraft. Aircrew reported strike to tower.  Flight was terminated and ground inspection by maintenance could (not) find impact point in the dark. Further inspection the next morning by maintenance revealed impact to be on the nose portion of the left side of the aircraft with no structural damage. Bird remains were collected and given to Wing Safety for identification. Maj Mark D. Hole, xxx-xxx-xxxx mark.hole@okang-okc.ang.af.mil

We were at about 900' MSL.  We changed from a touch-and-go landing to a full stop landing and terminated the flight.  Inspection of the plane by the flight engineers and maintenance did not disclose any damage.  The bird hit the pilot's window.

on rotation, 2 egrets flew in front of the aircraft.  We suspected one bird may have struck #2 engine as the "ICE" WAP message appeared at the same time.  We contnued the takeoff and monitored the engine indications which were all normal.  We thought we felt some vibration and put #2 engine in idle for the remainder of the flight.  We did an immediate return for an uneventful ILS to runway 15 full stop.  We taxied back to parking to have MXS inspect the engine.

Aircraft encountered a flock of seagulls sitting on the touch-down point of RWY 16. Aircraft was in the flare after breaking out of clouds at minimums. Wx at time was 200-1/2 with Fog and drizzle. Seagulls were feeding on clam shells thery had brought on to the field. They use the hard surface of the runway to break the shells open. They drop them from 10 feet up and then feed on the broken clams.  (In Rhode Island we refer to the hard shelled clam as a 'quahog'. I think that's an Indian name for clam.)

Robin

The aircrew was on a local proficiency sortie performing multitple approaches at KMDT. Immediately after landing the aircrew saw a single bird pass down the right side of the aircraft. Although the crew did not hear or see any indication that the bird struck the aircraft, they decided to full stop and inspect for damage. The crew also notified the airfield of the possibility of the strike. During the inspection, the crew found evidence of a strike and ground personnel found the remains of a hawk on the runway. The aircrew returned to Martinsburg to allow maintenance to thorough inspect the aircraft. Maintenance crews found evidence of a strike on the leading edge of the right wing between the number 3 and number 4 engines and a small dent in the right external fuel tank. Damage was determined to be minimal and the aircraft was relesased for flight.
Bird strike on left side of vertical stab

During takfeoff roll as number 2 in a 2 ship formation, the crew saw a small flock of birds fly up from the grass alongside the runway and into the path of thier aircraft. At 106 knots, 4 below takeoff speed, a single bird struck the aircraft below the pilots window. Believing the aircraft sufferred multiple strikes, the pilot decided to abort the take off and cancelled the mission to allow a thorough inspection of the aircraft prior to it's next flight.

AIRPORT: EGLIN AIR FORCE BASE/DESTIN-FORT WALTON BEACH AIRPORT
REMARKS: After takeoff, MP saw three large birds directly in his flight path.  The MP saw two birds dive down to avoid the aircraft while the other leveled off.  The MP executed an evasive maneuver, but the third bird impacted the aircraft.  Post-flight revealed extensive damage to the right inlet, engine, and conformal fuel tank.  It appears that part of the bird was split in half by the lower intake lip.  Impact point created a hole on the lower intake lip and ramp.  Half the bird went into the engine and half skipped off the right conformal fuel tank impacting the lower right wing surface and weapons pylons.  The majority of the bird went down the intake, impacting the first stage of the engine fan.  It damaged several first and second stage fan blades.

REMARKS: MISSION WAS PLANNED AND FLOWN AS A 2-SHIP FORMATION TACTICAL LOW LEVEL TRAINING SORTIE IN THE 137AW LATNA.  AFTER COMPLETING THE FORMATION PROTION OF THE FLIGHT, THE BIRD STRIKE AIRCRAFT ENTERED THE VISUAL TRAFFIC PATTERN FOR A PILOT SHORTFIELD LANDING EVALUATION.  BIRD STRIKE AIRCREW DID NOT SEE BIRD PRIOR TO STRIKE BUT HEARD BIRD IMPACT ON AIRCRAFT.  EVENT AIRCREW QUICKLY ASSESSED ENGINE INDICATIONS WHICH WERE NORMAL, AND CONTINUED APPROACH AND UNEVENTFUL FULL-STOP LANDING TO 3,090' LONG ASSAULT ZONE.  CONTACTED MDS QUALIFIED MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL WHO MET THE AIRCRAFT ON THE ANG PARKING RAMP FOR VISUAL INSPECTION OF AIRCRAFT.  MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL DETERMINED THERE WAS NO PHYSICAL DAMAGE TO AIRCRAFT AND RELEASED IT FOR CONTINUED FLIGHT BY FOLLOW-ON AIRCREW. THE FOLLOWING DAY DURING MAINTENANCE PREFLIGHT BPO INSPECTIONS, BIRD REMAINS WERE RECOVERED FROM THE LEFT SIDE OF THE NOSE RADOME (IMPACT POINT 1) AND THE TOP OF THE FUSELAGE (IMPACT POINT 2) ABOVE THE COCKPIT.  RADOME REMAINS APPEAR TO BE Falco sparverius, American Kestrel.  COMMON TO THE AREA AND INVOLVED IN PREVIOUS BIRD STRIKES AT KOKC.
